<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-731-100  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 731 100.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  August 13 1990 v24 n33 p7(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>E-mail lawsuit cranks open privacy rights can of worms.andO;(electronic mail)(Epson America Inc.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Nash, Jim.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>An invasion-of-privacy suit was filed against Epson America Inc byfour former and hundreds of current Epson employees who have usedthe company's electronic mail system since Aug 1989.andP;  The claimstates that the computer system manager, Robert Hillseth,illegally tapped messages passing through a gateway between thesystem and the external E-mail service.andP;  Damages of $3,000 perperson for each violation of a California statute concerning theinterception of electronic communication without all partiesconsenting are being sought.andP;  Epson has dismissed the claims,insisting that its unofficial policy is to read messages only whenthey get caught up in routine network administration ortroubleshooting.andP;  Epson issued an internal memorandum stating thatdata transmission equipment should only be used for business useand the privacy of documents stored anywhere in the company couldnot be guaranteed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Epson America Inc. (cases).andO;Topic:     Electronic mail systemsPrivacyPersonnelLegal IssuesCourt Cases.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>